                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d464">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5701</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs at
                            Nanking</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Chinese Legation</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="90" xml:id="d464fn90">Translation of telegram transmitted to the
                        Department by the Chinese Legation, December 29, 1932.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-29">December 29,
                            1932</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Wire from Peiping states that the Japanese have been storing large quantities of
                    provisions around <persName>Fu-Hsin</persName>, Jehol, (300 miles northeast of
                    Peiping) and that they have been spending large sums of money trying to enlist
                    Chinese people for resistance against Chinese forces.</p>
                <p>Reports from Tao-Nan and Tung-Liao state that three thousand additional Japanese
                    troops have arrived in preparation for a campaign toward Kai-Loo, Jehol, (250
                    miles northeast of Peiping).</p>
            </div>
        </body>
